  <header class="page-header header-no-img">
    <div class="title-wrapper">
    <h1 class="title" id="page-title">
      Meditation    </h1>
      </div>
</header>


      <div id="taxonomy-middle">
      <div class="term-description" data-read-more data-target-blank>
        <p>Meditation is the practice of taking a break from our daily activity and quieting the mind’s thoughts.</p>

<p>There are lots of different types of meditation, but one of the most popular is<a href="http://greatist.com/happiness/thinking-negative-thoughts-mindfulness-meditation"> mindfulness meditation</a>, which teaches us to reduce stress by becoming more aware of our thoughts and feelings.</p>

<p>Researchers are still uncovering the benefits of meditation, which include<a href="http://greatist.com/happiness/can-meditation-make-us-smarter"> boosting our cognitive function</a>,<a href="http://greatist.com/health/meditation-prevent-winter-sickness"> strengthening our immune system</a>, and reducing symptoms of depression and anxiety <cite data-cite-reference="" class="citation-reference"><a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1361002/">Meditation experience is associated with increased cortical thickness</a>. Lazar, S.W., Kerr, C.E., Wasserman, R.H., et al. Psychiatric Neuroimaging Research Program, Massachusetts General Hospital, Boston, Massachusetts, USA. Neuroreport 2005 Nov 28;16(17):1893-7.</cite><cite data-cite-reference="" class="citation-reference"><a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22778122">Meditation or exercise for preventing acute respiratory infection: a randomized controlled trial</a>. Barrett, B., Hayney, M.S., Muller, D., et al. Department of Family Medicine, University of Wisconsin – Madison, Madison, WI, USA. Annals of Family Medicine 2012 Jul-Aug;10(4):337-46.</cite> <cite data-cite-reference="" class="citation-reference"><a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22700446">Meditative therapies for reducing anxiety: a systematic review and meta-analysis of randomized controlled trials</a>. Chen, K.W., Berger, C.C., Manheimer, E., et al. Center for Integrative Medicine, University of Maryland School of Medicine, Baltimore, Maryland, USA. Depression and Anxiety 2012 Jul;29)7):545-62.</cite>.</p>

<h4>Learn more:</h4>

<p><a href="http://greatist.com/happiness/unexpected-ways-to-meditate">10 Unexpected Ways to Meditate Every Day</a><br /><a href="http://greatist.com/happiness/not-spiritual-why-you-can-still-meditate">Not Spiritual? Why You Can Still Meditate</a><br /><a href="http://greatist.com/happiness/thinking-negative-thoughts-mindfulness-meditation">How to Transform Negative Thoughts With Mindfulness Meditation</a><br /><a href="http://greatist.com/health/meditation-prevent-winter-sickness">Meditation Could Ward Off Winter Sickness</a><br /><a href="http://greatist.com/happiness/learning-to-meditate">Learning to Love Silence: Life-Changing Meditation</a><br /><a href="http://greatist.com/happiness/learn-to-meditate-zensperiment">40 Days of Meditation: #Zensperiment</a><br /><a href="http://greatist.com/happiness/can-meditation-make-us-smarter">Can Meditation Make Us Smarter?</a><br /><a href="http://greatist.com/happiness/mindfulness-meditation-physically-changes-brain">Mindfulness Meditation Physically Changes the Brain</a></p>
        <a href="#" class="read-more-taxonomy">
          <span>Read more</span> <i class="fa fa-caret-down"></i>
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  
    

